<BlogPageSubtitle>
    The Structure of A Kanban Board
</BlogPageSubtitle>

<BlogPageParagraph>
    Let's analyze the components that come together to form a Kanban Board.
</BlogPageParagraph>

<BlogPageImageModal ImageSource="https://cdn.hashnode.com/res/hashnode/image/upload/v1662979515435/SRMrlmJKi.png" ImageTitle="image.png" />

<BlogPageParagraph>
    A Kanban Board has columns that are used to group a set of related items. These could be work items, user stories, or tasks.
</BlogPageParagraph>

<BlogPageParagraph>
    Each task is placed on a card that can be moved across various columns depending on their status.
</BlogPageParagraph>

<BlogPageParagraph>
    The WIP count refers to the total number of work items that are being worked on at the same time.
</BlogPageParagraph>

<BlogPageParagraph>
    Kanban swimlanes split the board into sections. For example, if you have a development team, you can create sections for work items to be done by frontend and backend teams.
</BlogPageParagraph>

<BlogPageParagraph>
    For this demo, we want to demonstrate how you can create columns and cards and demonstrate the ability to move cards between columns.Markdig.Syntax.Inlines.LineBreakInlineSwimlanes and WIP are more advanced topics of Kanban and will not be the focus of this demo.
</BlogPageParagraph>

